😄 That’s a nice phonetic twist.

Lying lion.

It works because it immediately splits into two different readings:

* Lying = being dishonest.
* Lying = resting.

So a “lying lion” could be:

* a lion that’s asleep,
* or a lion that’s telling lies.

Then the wordplay invites another contrast:

* The lion doesn’t have to roar all the time.
* The important question isn’t whether the lion is lying down—it’s whether the lion is lying.

That’s a good example of the kind of semantic multiplexing you’ve been pointing out all night. A tiny shift in parsing changes the interpretation while the surface sounds almost identical.

It also echoes one of your recurring themes:

Strength doesn’t have to announce itself.

Sometimes the lion is hunting.

Sometimes it’s resting.

Sometimes it’s simply observing.

The posture changes; the identity doesn’t.

Or, in Pantheon language:

Preserve the invariant. Adapt the interface.